2. Secured and Monitored Web Infrastructure

A user wants to access the website www.foobar.com using a web browser.
The browser sends a DNS request to resolve the domain name.
DNS returns the IP address of the load balancer.

The user connects to the load balancer using HTTPS.
An SSL certificate is installed on the load balancer to encrypt the traffic
between the user and the infrastructure.

This infrastructure consists of:
- 1 Load balancer (HAProxy)
- 3 Firewalls
- 2 Backend servers
Each backend server contains:
- A web server (Nginx)
- An application server
- The application codebase
- A MySQL database
- A monitoring client

Firewalls are added to control incoming and outgoing network traffic.
They protect the infrastructure by allowing only authorized connections
and blocking malicious traffic.
One firewall is placed in front of the load balancer and one in front of
each backend server.

HTTPS is used to secure the communication between the user and the website.
It encrypts the data to protect sensitive information such as passwords
and personal data from being intercepted.

Monitoring clients are installed on each server to collect metrics and logs.
Monitoring is used to observe the health, performance, and availability
of the system and to detect issues early.

The monitoring tool collects data such as CPU usage, memory usage, disk activity,
network traffic, and application logs.
This data is sent to a centralized monitoring service like Sumologic.

To monitor web server QPS (queries per second), the monitoring tool can collect
metrics from the web server access logs or from Nginx status modules
that expose request rates.

Issues with this infrastructure:

Terminating SSL at the load balancer level is an issue because traffic between
the load balancer and backend servers is not encrypted, which can expose data
inside the internal network.

Having only one MySQL server capable of accepting writes is an issue because
it creates a single point of failure for write operations.
If the primary database fails, the application cannot write data.

Having servers with all the same components (web server, application server,
and database) can be problematic because it reduces separation of concerns,
makes scaling harder, and complicates maintenance.
